1
00:00:00,100 --> 00:00:02,931
(dramatic music)

2
00:00:02,931 --> 00:00:06,098
(audience applauding)

3
00:00:14,070 --> 00:00:15,420
- If you sleep well tonight,

4
00:00:15,420 --> 00:00:17,371
you may not have understood this lecture.

5
00:00:17,371 --> 00:00:20,371
(audience laughing)

6
00:00:23,610 --> 00:00:25,860
So, a long time ago,

7
00:00:25,860 --> 00:00:28,743
there were two paradigms for intelligence.

8
00:00:29,640 --> 00:00:33,930
There was a logic-inspired
approach, which was called AI.

9
00:00:33,930 --> 00:00:36,090
And people believed that the essence

10
00:00:36,090 --> 00:00:38,790
of human intelligence was reasoning.

11
00:00:38,790 --> 00:00:40,650
And if you want to
understand intelligence,

12
00:00:40,650 --> 00:00:42,780
you had to understand reasoning.

13
00:00:42,780 --> 00:00:45,960
And reasoning consisted of
having symbolic expressions

14
00:00:45,960 --> 00:00:48,273
and manipulating them with symbolic rules.

15
00:00:49,470 --> 00:00:51,180
And they thought that learning
could wait till later.

16
00:00:51,180 --> 00:00:52,290
First, we had to understand

17
00:00:52,290 --> 00:00:55,563
how you represent knowledge
in these symbolic expressions.

18
00:00:56,520 --> 00:00:58,560
And most of the history of AI,

19
00:00:58,560 --> 00:01:01,620
until fairly recently, was that.

20
00:01:01,620 --> 00:01:03,990
Then there was a biologically
inspired approach,

21
00:01:03,990 --> 00:01:05,720
where the essence of
intelligence is learning

22
00:01:05,720 --> 00:01:07,890
in a network of brain cells,

23
00:01:07,890 --> 00:01:09,000
in us, real ones,

24
00:01:09,000 --> 00:01:10,623
in computer, simulated ones.

25
00:01:11,520 --> 00:01:13,260
And reasoning can wait till later,

26
00:01:13,260 --> 00:01:15,370
we first have to understand
how learning works.

27
00:01:15,370 --> 00:01:18,000
There were a few early proponents of that,

28
00:01:18,000 --> 00:01:20,250
in particular Turing and von Neumann,

29
00:01:20,250 --> 00:01:21,360
and you couldn't really accuse them

30
00:01:21,360 --> 00:01:22,833
of not understanding logic.

31
00:01:24,630 --> 00:01:27,780
So I'm gonna give a fairly basic lecture,

32
00:01:27,780 --> 00:01:29,010
and for the first part of it,

33
00:01:29,010 --> 00:01:34,010
I'm gonna describe a model
I developed 40 years ago,

34
00:01:34,260 --> 00:01:35,790
which I see as the ancestor

35
00:01:35,790 --> 00:01:38,400
of these large language models of today.

36
00:01:38,400 --> 00:01:40,080
So we're gonna make our neural net

37
00:01:40,080 --> 00:01:42,330
out of artificial neurons.

38
00:01:42,330 --> 00:01:44,970
And an artificial neuron is
gonna have some input lines,

39
00:01:44,970 --> 00:01:46,740
typically coming from other neurons,

40
00:01:46,740 --> 00:01:48,960
it's gonna have weights
on those input lines.

41
00:01:48,960 --> 00:01:50,610
It's gonna multiply the
inputs by the weights,

42
00:01:50,610 --> 00:01:53,850
add all up, and then give an output,

43
00:01:53,850 --> 00:01:55,260
which is shown by that graph there.

44
00:01:55,260 --> 00:01:57,060
So if it gets above its threshold,

45
00:01:57,060 --> 00:01:59,040
it gives an output that linearly increases

46
00:01:59,040 --> 00:02:00,140
as it gets more input.

47
00:02:01,020 --> 00:02:02,010
And the way it's gonna learn

48
00:02:02,010 --> 00:02:05,460
is just by changing the
weights on those connections.

49
00:02:05,460 --> 00:02:07,950
So all we need to do to make
artificial neural networks work

50
00:02:07,950 --> 00:02:09,950
is figure out how to change the weights.

51
00:02:11,070 --> 00:02:13,680
We hook them up into networks.

52
00:02:13,680 --> 00:02:16,650
This is a typical network,
it's a feedforward network,

53
00:02:16,650 --> 00:02:20,190
where at the bottom, you
might have sensory neurons

54
00:02:20,190 --> 00:02:23,550
that are recording light
intensities or something like that.

55
00:02:23,550 --> 00:02:25,740
And as you go up through the
layers, you have many layers

56
00:02:25,740 --> 00:02:28,650
of feature detectors that is
the neurons turn into things

57
00:02:28,650 --> 00:02:31,440
that recognise particular
features in an image.

58
00:02:31,440 --> 00:02:33,030
And at the output, you might have neurons

59
00:02:33,030 --> 00:02:35,080
to represent particular classes of thing.

60
00:02:36,450 --> 00:02:38,730
Now, if you want a
network like that to learn

61
00:02:38,730 --> 00:02:40,560
to be better at doing something,

62
00:02:40,560 --> 00:02:42,660
so you want to give it
an image and have it say,

63
00:02:42,660 --> 00:02:45,090
for example, whether
there's a cat or a dog,

64
00:02:45,090 --> 00:02:47,070
there's an obvious way to train it,

65
00:02:47,070 --> 00:02:48,090
which goes to everybody

66
00:02:48,090 --> 00:02:50,283
who knows about evolution and mutations.

67
00:02:51,120 --> 00:02:54,210
What you can do is, you can
take one of the weights,

68
00:02:54,210 --> 00:02:58,140
and you can first see
how well the network does

69
00:02:58,140 --> 00:02:59,637
on a whole bunch of examples,

70
00:02:59,637 --> 00:03:02,130
and then change the weight just slightly,

71
00:03:02,130 --> 00:03:03,300
and see how well the network does

72
00:03:03,300 --> 00:03:04,290
on a whole bunch of examples.

73
00:03:04,290 --> 00:03:06,630
And if it does better,
you keep that change,

74
00:03:06,630 --> 00:03:08,310
and you just keep going like that.

75
00:03:08,310 --> 00:03:11,430
Now, you probably need to
change each weight many times.

76
00:03:11,430 --> 00:03:13,950
And there's a lot of weights
in modern neural networks,

77
00:03:13,950 --> 00:03:15,180
there's about a trillion.

78
00:03:15,180 --> 00:03:17,130
So that's gonna take a long time,

79
00:03:17,130 --> 00:03:19,980
'cause for each mutation
you make like that,

80
00:03:19,980 --> 00:03:21,690
you have to run many
examples through the net

81
00:03:21,690 --> 00:03:23,100
to see if it really helps,

82
00:03:23,100 --> 00:03:24,480
or if it just helps on a few examples,

83
00:03:24,480 --> 00:03:25,780
but hurts on most of them.

84
00:03:27,240 --> 00:03:29,610
There's a better way to do the same thing,

85
00:03:29,610 --> 00:03:31,170
that is what we really
want to do is figure out

86
00:03:31,170 --> 00:03:33,570
how to change your
weight so that it helps.

87
00:03:33,570 --> 00:03:35,460
What you do is, you do a forward pass,

88
00:03:35,460 --> 00:03:36,510
you put the data in the bottom,

89
00:03:36,510 --> 00:03:38,280
you go forward through the network,

90
00:03:38,280 --> 00:03:40,980
and you compare what
came out of the network,

91
00:03:40,980 --> 00:03:42,570
which might be the relative probabilities

92
00:03:42,570 --> 00:03:44,250
of it being a cat and a dog,

93
00:03:44,250 --> 00:03:45,870
with what you want.

94
00:03:45,870 --> 00:03:47,730
You have to know whether
it's a cat or a dog

95
00:03:47,730 --> 00:03:49,650
to train networks this way.

96
00:03:49,650 --> 00:03:52,800
And then you send a signal
backwards through the network

97
00:03:52,800 --> 00:03:55,770
that using calculus, which
I'm not gonna go into,

98
00:03:55,770 --> 00:03:58,980
allows the network to
compute at the same time

99
00:03:58,980 --> 00:04:01,920
for all connections,
whether a small increase

100
00:04:01,920 --> 00:04:05,100
in the connection strength
would help or hurt.

101
00:04:05,100 --> 00:04:07,260
And then you change all the
connection strengths in parallel

102
00:04:07,260 --> 00:04:08,670
by a very small amount

103
00:04:08,670 --> 00:04:11,430
in proportion to how much
they would help or hurt.

104
00:04:11,430 --> 00:04:12,750
And if you do that,

105
00:04:12,750 --> 00:04:15,810
it's gonna get better at the
examples you've trained it on.

106
00:04:15,810 --> 00:04:18,840
And in fact, that works extremely well.

107
00:04:18,840 --> 00:04:20,760
It took a long time for people to realise

108
00:04:20,760 --> 00:04:24,000
how well that relatively
simple algorithm works.

109
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:26,280
The algorithm was discovered many times,

110
00:04:26,280 --> 00:04:27,680
it's called backpropagation.

111
00:04:29,190 --> 00:04:33,480
And in 2012, two of my students,

112
00:04:33,480 --> 00:04:35,091
Alex Krizhevsky and Ilya Sutskever,

113
00:04:35,091 --> 00:04:38,996
who's famous now for firing Sam Altman,

114
00:04:38,996 --> 00:04:40,800
(audience laughing)

115
00:04:40,800 --> 00:04:43,260
developed a network called AlexNet

116
00:04:43,260 --> 00:04:47,220
that was much better than
existing image division systems

117
00:04:47,220 --> 00:04:48,963
at recognising objects in images.

118
00:04:49,980 --> 00:04:54,090
And that led to sort
of open the floodgates.

119
00:04:54,090 --> 00:04:54,923
Up until that point,

120
00:04:54,923 --> 00:04:56,820
neural nets had been good for many things,

121
00:04:56,820 --> 00:04:58,500
including speech recognition,

122
00:04:58,500 --> 00:05:00,480
but they hadn't really taken over.

123
00:05:00,480 --> 00:05:02,640
From that point on, they really took over.

124
00:05:02,640 --> 00:05:05,040
And now, when you say "AI,"

125
00:05:05,040 --> 00:05:08,433
what people mean by AI is
neural networks, it's not logic.

126
00:05:10,543 --> 00:05:12,960
But what about language?

127
00:05:12,960 --> 00:05:15,690
So there's a whole community
that studies language,

128
00:05:15,690 --> 00:05:17,340
I think they're called linguists,

129
00:05:18,810 --> 00:05:21,210
and they have a very strong idea

130
00:05:21,210 --> 00:05:23,580
about how you should study language,

131
00:05:23,580 --> 00:05:25,260
and particularly, the Chomsky school.

132
00:05:25,260 --> 00:05:26,490
They were very sceptical

133
00:05:26,490 --> 00:05:29,340
that neural networks could
do anything with language.

134
00:05:29,340 --> 00:05:30,750
They were completely convinced

135
00:05:30,750 --> 00:05:33,363
that it's all about symbolic expressions.

136
00:05:35,040 --> 00:05:37,020
They didn't really have the idea

137
00:05:37,020 --> 00:05:40,860
that the real function of
language is to give you words

138
00:05:40,860 --> 00:05:43,590
which are bricks from
which you can build models.

139
00:05:43,590 --> 00:05:45,900
Language is a modelling medium.

140
00:05:45,900 --> 00:05:47,940
They were focused on syntax.

141
00:05:47,940 --> 00:05:49,710
And syntax isn't the main point.

142
00:05:49,710 --> 00:05:51,810
The main point is,
language is a wonderful way

143
00:05:51,810 --> 00:05:53,940
to build a particular
kind of complicated model,

144
00:05:53,940 --> 00:05:54,773
as we'll see.

145
00:05:57,480 --> 00:05:58,590
Okay.

146
00:05:58,590 --> 00:05:59,460
They also thought

147
00:05:59,460 --> 00:06:02,610
that knowledge of language was innate,

148
00:06:02,610 --> 00:06:04,230
knowledge of syntax was innate,

149
00:06:04,230 --> 00:06:05,575
which is just stupid.

150
00:06:05,575 --> 00:06:07,530
(audience laughing)

151
00:06:07,530 --> 00:06:09,240
It's the sign of a cult,

152
00:06:09,240 --> 00:06:10,560
that in order to join the cult,

153
00:06:10,560 --> 00:06:12,690
you have to believe something
that's obviously silly,

154
00:06:12,690 --> 00:06:14,447
like language isn't learned.

155
00:06:14,447 --> 00:06:15,870
(audience laughing)

156
00:06:15,870 --> 00:06:17,460
Okay.

157
00:06:17,460 --> 00:06:19,470
So here's two very different theories

158
00:06:19,470 --> 00:06:21,210
of the meaning of a word.

159
00:06:21,210 --> 00:06:22,770
The symbolic AI theory,

160
00:06:22,770 --> 00:06:26,700
which goes back to kind
of dissasura, a long way,

161
00:06:26,700 --> 00:06:27,960
is that the meaning of a word

162
00:06:27,960 --> 00:06:29,880
is to do with its
relationships to other words,

163
00:06:29,880 --> 00:06:31,350
you can't justify it by itself

164
00:06:31,350 --> 00:06:33,050
without talking about other words.

165
00:06:34,110 --> 00:06:35,340
And so to capture meaning,

166
00:06:35,340 --> 00:06:38,220
we need something like a relational graph.

167
00:06:38,220 --> 00:06:40,500
But then the psychologists,

168
00:06:40,500 --> 00:06:42,930
who particularly from the 1930s, I think,

169
00:06:42,930 --> 00:06:45,690
who thought the meaning of a
word is a big set of features.

170
00:06:45,690 --> 00:06:49,260
So "Tuesday" has a big
set of active features,

171
00:06:49,260 --> 00:06:51,243
and "Wednesday" has a big
set of active features

172
00:06:51,243 --> 00:06:53,550
that are almost the same.

173
00:06:53,550 --> 00:06:54,990
So the idea that the meaning of a words,

174
00:06:54,990 --> 00:06:56,460
a set of active features is very good

175
00:06:56,460 --> 00:06:57,960
for saying which words
means similar things

176
00:06:57,960 --> 00:06:59,010
to which other words.

177
00:07:00,150 --> 00:07:03,540
These look like two very
different theories of meaning.

178
00:07:03,540 --> 00:07:05,010
Now, what I want to do is show you

179
00:07:05,010 --> 00:07:06,963
that these two theories can be unified.

180
00:07:08,100 --> 00:07:09,390
They're not two different theories,

181
00:07:09,390 --> 00:07:11,290
they're two halves of the same theory.

182
00:07:12,750 --> 00:07:16,320
So, and what I'm gonna do is
talk for quite a long time now

183
00:07:16,320 --> 00:07:19,320
about a very little model,
a tiny neural network.

184
00:07:19,320 --> 00:07:22,923
It had a few thousand connections
and a few dozen neurons.

185
00:07:24,420 --> 00:07:27,870
I developed it in 1985
to try to understand

186
00:07:27,870 --> 00:07:30,870
how people could learn
the meanings of words.

187
00:07:30,870 --> 00:07:32,190
And I was very excited

188
00:07:32,190 --> 00:07:35,400
about how it unified these
two theories of meaning,

189
00:07:35,400 --> 00:07:36,828
and nobody else was.

190
00:07:36,828 --> 00:07:39,000
(audience laughing)

191
00:07:39,000 --> 00:07:43,210
Okay, so what we're gonna
do in this little model

192
00:07:44,160 --> 00:07:47,490
is learn how to make
the features of one word

193
00:07:47,490 --> 00:07:51,450
predict the features of the
next word in a little sentence.

194
00:07:51,450 --> 00:07:53,040
And then once we know the
features of the next word,

195
00:07:53,040 --> 00:07:54,810
we can predict the next word.

196
00:07:54,810 --> 00:07:57,120
And we are not gonna store any sentences.

197
00:07:57,120 --> 00:07:57,953
So many people say,

198
00:07:57,953 --> 00:08:00,090
"Big chat bots are just
regurgitating stuff."

199
00:08:00,090 --> 00:08:02,970
Big chat bots don't actually
store any language at all.

200
00:08:02,970 --> 00:08:04,830
They don't store strings of words.

201
00:08:04,830 --> 00:08:07,740
They just store how to
turn words into features,

202
00:08:07,740 --> 00:08:09,690
and how features should
interact with each other

203
00:08:09,690 --> 00:08:11,460
to predict the features of the next word.

204
00:08:11,460 --> 00:08:13,980
That's all that's in
these chat bots, no words.

205
00:08:13,980 --> 00:08:15,120
But when they wanna produce a sentence,

206
00:08:15,120 --> 00:08:17,220
they have to make it up as they go,

207
00:08:17,220 --> 00:08:20,013
and they often can't tell
whether it was real or not.

208
00:08:22,410 --> 00:08:25,350
Okay, so what's gonna
happen in this little model

209
00:08:25,350 --> 00:08:27,090
is if it wants to produce a new sentence,

210
00:08:27,090 --> 00:08:29,240
it has to just make it
up a word at a time.

211
00:08:31,560 --> 00:08:32,880
And all the relational knowledge

212
00:08:32,880 --> 00:08:34,613
is just in how you turn
the word into features,

213
00:08:34,613 --> 00:08:36,393
and how these features interact.

214
00:08:37,620 --> 00:08:42,251
So the example I chose to
use was two family trees,

215
00:08:42,251 --> 00:08:45,900
an English family tree and
an Italian family tree,

216
00:08:45,900 --> 00:08:49,203
they're isomorphic, which
is helpful for learning.

217
00:08:50,730 --> 00:08:52,530
And I wanted a little neural network

218
00:08:52,530 --> 00:08:55,140
to learn the knowledge
in those family trees.

219
00:08:55,140 --> 00:08:57,060
This was a long time ago in 1985,

220
00:08:57,060 --> 00:08:59,700
when computers were
billions of times slower

221
00:08:59,700 --> 00:09:02,040
than the big parallel computers

222
00:09:02,040 --> 00:09:03,840
we use for training models nowadays.

223
00:09:05,190 --> 00:09:07,710
Now, the knowledge in those
trees can be represented

224
00:09:07,710 --> 00:09:09,780
as a bunch of propositions, which is,

225
00:09:09,780 --> 00:09:11,180
the symbolic eyes love that.

226
00:09:12,510 --> 00:09:14,580
So here they are.

227
00:09:14,580 --> 00:09:16,590
We can use relationships
like son, daughter,

228
00:09:16,590 --> 00:09:17,697
nephew, niece, and so on.

229
00:09:17,697 --> 00:09:20,010
And we can define the knowledge,

230
00:09:20,010 --> 00:09:23,700
we can represent the
knowledge as strings of words.

231
00:09:23,700 --> 00:09:26,280
So the knowledge is in these sentences.

232
00:09:26,280 --> 00:09:27,870
So Colin has Father James,

233
00:09:27,870 --> 00:09:29,460
and Colin has Mother Victoria.

234
00:09:29,460 --> 00:09:31,500
From that, if you know the rules,

235
00:09:31,500 --> 00:09:35,010
you can infer that
James has wife Victoria.

236
00:09:35,010 --> 00:09:37,680
This is a 1950s American family

237
00:09:37,680 --> 00:09:39,346
that's never heard of divorce or adoption.

238
00:09:39,346 --> 00:09:42,056
(audience laughing)

239
00:09:42,056 --> 00:09:44,963
And they're clearly all white.

240
00:09:44,963 --> 00:09:47,670
(audience laughing)

241
00:09:47,670 --> 00:09:49,680
Okay, so you can represent the knowledge

242
00:09:49,680 --> 00:09:51,423
as strings of words.

243
00:09:53,580 --> 00:09:56,160
Now, you can think of a
relational learning task

244
00:09:56,160 --> 00:09:58,080
as I give you the beginning
of a string of words,

245
00:09:58,080 --> 00:09:59,580
and you give me the last word.

246
00:10:01,200 --> 00:10:04,237
So if you were doing this
with symbolic AI, you'd say,

247
00:10:04,237 --> 00:10:07,530
"Well, we have regularities
in this domain of the form,

248
00:10:07,530 --> 00:10:10,950
if X has mother Y, and Y has husband Z,

249
00:10:10,950 --> 00:10:13,050
then X has father Z."

250
00:10:13,050 --> 00:10:14,970
That would be the symbolic way to do it.

251
00:10:14,970 --> 00:10:16,200
But I want to do it a different way.

252
00:10:16,200 --> 00:10:18,000
I want to do it by
learning features for words

253
00:10:18,000 --> 00:10:20,010
and having interactions of features.

254
00:10:20,010 --> 00:10:23,430
And that would involve
searching a big continuous space

255
00:10:23,430 --> 00:10:27,090
of connection strengths instead
of a small discreet space

256
00:10:27,090 --> 00:10:30,003
of rules that are discreet.

257
00:10:32,790 --> 00:10:34,743
So this was the network I used.

258
00:10:35,631 --> 00:10:38,217
The inputs were a bunch of neurons,

259
00:10:38,217 --> 00:10:40,830
and you turn on one neuron

260
00:10:40,830 --> 00:10:43,290
for the symbol representing person one.

261
00:10:43,290 --> 00:10:47,160
There were 24 possible person ones,

262
00:10:47,160 --> 00:10:49,050
and you turn on one neuron

263
00:10:49,050 --> 00:10:50,880
for the symbol representing
the relationship,

264
00:10:50,880 --> 00:10:53,100
there were 12 possible relationships,

265
00:10:53,100 --> 00:10:55,650
then those single active neurons

266
00:10:55,650 --> 00:10:57,990
will get expanded into a feature vector.

267
00:10:57,990 --> 00:11:01,650
So the one neuron that you
turned on for person one

268
00:11:01,650 --> 00:11:04,170
will get expanded into
a little feature vector

269
00:11:04,170 --> 00:11:05,280
of six features,

270
00:11:05,280 --> 00:11:06,750
which could have various activity levels,

271
00:11:06,750 --> 00:11:08,160
some will be off, some will be on,

272
00:11:08,160 --> 00:11:09,270
some might be half off

273
00:11:09,270 --> 00:11:10,953
or fully on or fully off.

274
00:11:12,780 --> 00:11:14,400
And so the neural network had to learn

275
00:11:14,400 --> 00:11:18,180
how to convert a word symbol
into a little feature vector

276
00:11:18,180 --> 00:11:20,130
both for the person and the relationship.

277
00:11:20,130 --> 00:11:21,630
And then it had to learn

278
00:11:21,630 --> 00:11:23,580
how to take these two feature vectors

279
00:11:23,580 --> 00:11:26,520
for a person in relationship,
have the features interact,

280
00:11:26,520 --> 00:11:27,900
and for that I used a hidden layer,

281
00:11:27,900 --> 00:11:29,400
an extra layer of places

282
00:11:29,400 --> 00:11:32,700
where things could interact
to predict the features

283
00:11:32,700 --> 00:11:34,080
of the output person.

284
00:11:34,080 --> 00:11:35,850
And once you knew the
features of the output person,

285
00:11:35,850 --> 00:11:36,990
you can make a good good guess

286
00:11:36,990 --> 00:11:40,530
about who the output person
was and give an output.

287
00:11:40,530 --> 00:11:42,660
And the output would consist
of giving various levels

288
00:11:42,660 --> 00:11:45,720
of activation to the 24
possible output people.

289
00:11:45,720 --> 00:11:48,270
And you want the neural net to
give a high level activation

290
00:11:48,270 --> 00:11:49,740
to the right answer

291
00:11:49,740 --> 00:11:50,880
and a low level activation

292
00:11:50,880 --> 00:11:51,930
to the wrong answers.

293
00:11:53,730 --> 00:11:54,563
So,

294
00:11:56,820 --> 00:12:00,240
what happened is the six feature neurons

295
00:12:00,240 --> 00:12:03,300
that were the sort of
expansion of the person,

296
00:12:03,300 --> 00:12:06,420
it's 24 people, you
expand that active neuron

297
00:12:06,420 --> 00:12:09,319
into a feature vector
of six active features.

298
00:12:09,319 --> 00:12:13,680
They learned to be
sensible semantic features.

299
00:12:13,680 --> 00:12:14,820
They learn to be features

300
00:12:14,820 --> 00:12:16,650
that represented things
like the generation

301
00:12:16,650 --> 00:12:18,390
of the input person

302
00:12:18,390 --> 00:12:22,320
and the six features of the relationship

303
00:12:22,320 --> 00:12:24,420
learn to be sensible features,

304
00:12:24,420 --> 00:12:27,540
like, does this relationship
require the output person

305
00:12:27,540 --> 00:12:29,970
to be one generation up
from the input person?

306
00:12:29,970 --> 00:12:32,970
So something like fathers like
that where his brother isn't.

307
00:12:35,160 --> 00:12:36,420
And then the interactions

308
00:12:36,420 --> 00:12:38,790
between these features learn things like,

309
00:12:38,790 --> 00:12:41,340
if the input person is a generation three,

310
00:12:41,340 --> 00:12:42,780
and the relationship requires the person

311
00:12:42,780 --> 00:12:44,070
to be one generation up,

312
00:12:44,070 --> 00:12:46,470
then the output person
is a generation two.

313
00:12:46,470 --> 00:12:49,020
So for that little feature of
vector for the output person,

314
00:12:49,020 --> 00:12:52,470
it would activate the thing
that represents generation two.

315
00:12:52,470 --> 00:12:54,630
And it learned a whole bunch
of little rules like that,

316
00:12:54,630 --> 00:12:56,970
which really did capture
the structure of the domain.

317
00:12:56,970 --> 00:12:58,050
They're the kinds of rules

318
00:12:58,050 --> 00:13:00,390
that a symbolic person might
have written down as rules.

319
00:13:00,390 --> 00:13:04,530
But it just learned
those by trying to get,

320
00:13:04,530 --> 00:13:06,090
predict the right word,

321
00:13:06,090 --> 00:13:08,160
and then back propagating the error,

322
00:13:08,160 --> 00:13:10,260
sending information
back through the network

323
00:13:10,260 --> 00:13:12,600
to slightly change all
the connection strengths,

324
00:13:12,600 --> 00:13:13,650
so that next time,

325
00:13:13,650 --> 00:13:15,630
it will get higher probability
for the right answer

326
00:13:15,630 --> 00:13:17,723
and lower probability
for the wrong answer.

327
00:13:20,670 --> 00:13:24,153
So it had actually learned
to predict the next word,

328
00:13:25,050 --> 00:13:27,000
and you could understand
how it was doing it.

329
00:13:27,000 --> 00:13:28,260
It was a tiny net,

330
00:13:28,260 --> 00:13:30,090
so you could look and
see what was going on.

331
00:13:30,090 --> 00:13:32,040
You could see the
features that were using.

332
00:13:32,040 --> 00:13:33,960
You could see that it extracted a feature

333
00:13:33,960 --> 00:13:35,130
that was generational,

334
00:13:35,130 --> 00:13:37,890
which had three alternative values,

335
00:13:37,890 --> 00:13:40,290
off, medium, and fully on.

336
00:13:40,290 --> 00:13:41,940
And you could see that from relationships

337
00:13:41,940 --> 00:13:44,550
that had extracted a feature
like one generation up.

338
00:13:44,550 --> 00:13:45,843
And you could see those
would interact to predict

339
00:13:45,843 --> 00:13:47,640
that the output should be generation two

340
00:13:47,640 --> 00:13:49,740
if the import was generation three.

341
00:13:49,740 --> 00:13:51,120
So you understood how it worked,

342
00:13:51,120 --> 00:13:53,377
and in fact the symbolic
people didn't say,

343
00:13:53,377 --> 00:13:55,110
"That's not understanding,"

344
00:13:55,110 --> 00:13:57,090
the symbolic people said, "Yeah, okay,

345
00:13:57,090 --> 00:13:58,110
so it solved the problem,

346
00:13:58,110 --> 00:14:00,090
it's understood what the
rules are in this domain,

347
00:14:00,090 --> 00:14:03,720
but you're stupid to search
a space of real values,

348
00:14:03,720 --> 00:14:06,470
when you could be searching
a discreet space of rules."

349
00:14:07,620 --> 00:14:09,600
And there's something in that,

350
00:14:09,600 --> 00:14:11,610
except as soon as you get to real data,

351
00:14:11,610 --> 00:14:14,700
which is messy, and has exceptions,

352
00:14:14,700 --> 00:14:16,560
and things that are only probably true,

353
00:14:16,560 --> 00:14:19,320
it's much better to search
this space of real values

354
00:14:19,320 --> 00:14:20,340
than to have discreet rules

355
00:14:20,340 --> 00:14:22,840
'cause these discrete rules
keep getting violated.

356
00:14:23,700 --> 00:14:27,018
So about 10 years after I'd done that,

357
00:14:27,018 --> 00:14:30,410
Yoshua Bengio showed that
instead of just doing it

358
00:14:30,410 --> 00:14:32,820
on a toy little domain
with only a few people

359
00:14:32,820 --> 00:14:34,170
and a few relationships,

360
00:14:34,170 --> 00:14:35,760
you could actually do
it with English words.

361
00:14:35,760 --> 00:14:38,100
You could take English sentences,

362
00:14:38,100 --> 00:14:41,880
you have more input words, not just two.

363
00:14:41,880 --> 00:14:44,193
He had about 5, even 10.

364
00:14:45,870 --> 00:14:49,710
And you could actually predict
the next word quite well,

365
00:14:49,710 --> 00:14:52,203
about as well as the best
language models could.

366
00:14:53,910 --> 00:14:56,640
About 10 years after Yoshua
Bengio had shown that,

367
00:14:56,640 --> 00:14:58,957
the linguists finally decided that,

368
00:14:58,957 --> 00:14:59,910
"Actually, hey,

369
00:14:59,910 --> 00:15:02,280
having these feature vectors
to capture the meanings

370
00:15:02,280 --> 00:15:04,830
of words is quite a good idea."

371
00:15:04,830 --> 00:15:07,200
And about 10 years after that,

372
00:15:07,200 --> 00:15:09,450
people at Google invented transformers,

373
00:15:09,450 --> 00:15:10,890
which are particular architecture

374
00:15:10,890 --> 00:15:12,240
that I'm not gonna go into.

375
00:15:13,620 --> 00:15:16,860
And those transformers
made these models very good

376
00:15:16,860 --> 00:15:18,900
at predicting the next word,

377
00:15:18,900 --> 00:15:20,280
but they were doing it

378
00:15:20,280 --> 00:15:23,010
in just the way my tiny
language model was doing

379
00:15:23,010 --> 00:15:24,390
at a very crude level.

380
00:15:24,390 --> 00:15:27,450
They were turning words
into feature activations,

381
00:15:27,450 --> 00:15:29,010
having the features interact

382
00:15:29,010 --> 00:15:30,720
to predict the features of the next word,

383
00:15:30,720 --> 00:15:32,640
and then from that
predicting the next word,

384
00:15:32,640 --> 00:15:35,700
and then take the error
in your prediction,

385
00:15:35,700 --> 00:15:38,880
and send information
backwards through the network

386
00:15:38,880 --> 00:15:41,670
to learn all those
interactions between features

387
00:15:41,670 --> 00:15:44,400
and to learn how to turn
words into features.

388
00:15:44,400 --> 00:15:46,140
Now, the important thing
about my tiny model

389
00:15:46,140 --> 00:15:49,320
is it wasn't made to be practical.

390
00:15:49,320 --> 00:15:54,320
It wasn't made to be useful for
processing natural language.

391
00:15:54,330 --> 00:15:56,130
It was made as a theory

392
00:15:56,130 --> 00:15:58,800
of how people get the senses of words

393
00:15:58,800 --> 00:16:00,273
just from hearing sentences.

394
00:16:01,410 --> 00:16:02,670
Because we can do that.

395
00:16:02,670 --> 00:16:04,530
I can give you a new sentence

396
00:16:04,530 --> 00:16:06,390
with the words you've never heard before,

397
00:16:06,390 --> 00:16:08,400
and you will figure out
the meaning of that word

398
00:16:08,400 --> 00:16:10,050
in one sentence.

399
00:16:10,050 --> 00:16:11,947
Okay, here goes,

400
00:16:11,947 --> 00:16:15,161
"She scrammed him with the frying pan."

401
00:16:15,161 --> 00:16:16,320
(audience laughing)

402
00:16:16,320 --> 00:16:18,697
Now, you know it could have been,

403
00:16:18,697 --> 00:16:20,520
"She was very good at cooking omelettes

404
00:16:20,520 --> 00:16:22,500
and cooking omelettes with the frying pan

405
00:16:22,500 --> 00:16:23,430
really impressed him,

406
00:16:23,430 --> 00:16:25,020
so scrum means impressed."

407
00:16:25,020 --> 00:16:26,040
And that's a possibility,

408
00:16:26,040 --> 00:16:27,806
but you know what I really meant.

409
00:16:27,806 --> 00:16:29,700
(audience laughing)

410
00:16:29,700 --> 00:16:31,701
She hit him over the
head with a frying pan

411
00:16:31,701 --> 00:16:32,534
(audience laughing)

412
00:16:32,534 --> 00:16:33,896
because he deserved it.

413
00:16:33,896 --> 00:16:35,490
(audience laughing)

414
00:16:35,490 --> 00:16:37,990
Okay, so that's one sentence,
you get the meaning.

415
00:16:39,180 --> 00:16:40,980
So that's what I was trying to understand

416
00:16:40,980 --> 00:16:42,660
how you can do that.

417
00:16:42,660 --> 00:16:45,600
And when these linguists now, say like,

418
00:16:45,600 --> 00:16:46,770
there's a guy called Chomsky,

419
00:16:46,770 --> 00:16:48,277
when they say things like,

420
00:16:48,277 --> 00:16:49,650
"These things don't understand anything,

421
00:16:49,650 --> 00:16:52,050
they're just a statistical trick,"

422
00:16:52,050 --> 00:16:55,380
they don't actually have a
model of what understanding is,

423
00:16:55,380 --> 00:16:56,490
'cause they never really had a model

424
00:16:56,490 --> 00:16:57,677
of what understanding was.

425
00:16:57,677 --> 00:16:59,493
It was all about syntax.

426
00:17:01,170 --> 00:17:02,880
And if you ask what's the best model

427
00:17:02,880 --> 00:17:03,930
we have of understanding,

428
00:17:03,930 --> 00:17:06,420
it's these large language models.

429
00:17:06,420 --> 00:17:08,250
The tiny language model is built

430
00:17:08,250 --> 00:17:09,510
to try and model

431
00:17:09,510 --> 00:17:12,390
how humans understand
the meanings of words.

432
00:17:12,390 --> 00:17:13,710
It's now got a lot better

433
00:17:13,710 --> 00:17:15,060
as technology's got a lot faster

434
00:17:15,060 --> 00:17:16,560
and data sets have got bigger.

435
00:17:17,430 --> 00:17:19,080
But that is understanding.

436
00:17:19,080 --> 00:17:22,920
So my claim is that the
large language models,

437
00:17:22,920 --> 00:17:24,390
which I like to think are descendants

438
00:17:24,390 --> 00:17:25,890
of my tiny language model,

439
00:17:25,890 --> 00:17:27,300
although most of the people who make them

440
00:17:27,300 --> 00:17:28,855
have never heard of my
tiny language model,

441
00:17:28,855 --> 00:17:30,330
(audience laughing)

442
00:17:30,330 --> 00:17:32,400
they use many more words as input.

443
00:17:32,400 --> 00:17:34,170
They use many more layers of neurons.

444
00:17:34,170 --> 00:17:36,990
They have to do things I didn't
do like disambiguate words.

445
00:17:36,990 --> 00:17:38,430
If you have a word like "May,"

446
00:17:38,430 --> 00:17:39,450
it could be a month,

447
00:17:39,450 --> 00:17:40,800
it could be a woman's name,

448
00:17:40,800 --> 00:17:43,200
it could be a modal like would and should.

449
00:17:43,200 --> 00:17:45,540
And you can't just associate
a feature vector with it

450
00:17:45,540 --> 00:17:47,100
that captures the meaning directly.

451
00:17:47,100 --> 00:17:48,480
You have to hedge your bets.

452
00:17:48,480 --> 00:17:50,610
And then as you go up through
layers of the network,

453
00:17:50,610 --> 00:17:53,760
you disambiguate it using
influences from nearby things

454
00:17:53,760 --> 00:17:56,566
like if it's in April, May, June,

455
00:17:56,566 --> 00:17:59,250
that could still be the
name of three women,

456
00:17:59,250 --> 00:18:00,513
but less likely.

457
00:18:01,800 --> 00:18:02,633
Okay.

458
00:18:03,840 --> 00:18:05,310
So, they use many more words,

459
00:18:05,310 --> 00:18:06,510
they use many more layers,

460
00:18:06,510 --> 00:18:08,580
and the interactions they
have between features

461
00:18:08,580 --> 00:18:10,050
are much more complicated.

462
00:18:10,050 --> 00:18:12,900
I would just have features
feeding into another feature.

463
00:18:12,900 --> 00:18:15,870
They look at sets of features,

464
00:18:15,870 --> 00:18:18,120
and sets of features figure out messages

465
00:18:18,120 --> 00:18:20,257
to tend to other words to say,

466
00:18:20,257 --> 00:18:24,237
"Do you have a a key
that matches my query?"

467
00:18:25,500 --> 00:18:27,720
It's much more complicated
interactions, I won't go into,

468
00:18:27,720 --> 00:18:29,400
but the essence of it is the same.

469
00:18:29,400 --> 00:18:31,590
You're trying to predict the next word.

470
00:18:31,590 --> 00:18:33,330
You do it in a more complicated way,

471
00:18:33,330 --> 00:18:35,640
it's all done with features
and then interactions,

472
00:18:35,640 --> 00:18:36,810
when you get it wrong,

473
00:18:36,810 --> 00:18:38,250
you back propagate information

474
00:18:38,250 --> 00:18:40,980
that learns all these features
and then interactions.

475
00:18:40,980 --> 00:18:43,230
That's how language works for us,

476
00:18:43,230 --> 00:18:45,900
and it's how it works for
these large language models.

477
00:18:45,900 --> 00:18:47,340
We are basically the same.

478
00:18:47,340 --> 00:18:50,850
So the point here is they're very like us.

479
00:18:50,850 --> 00:18:53,490
They're very unlike computer software.

480
00:18:53,490 --> 00:18:54,323
Computer software,

481
00:18:54,323 --> 00:18:56,460
someone wrote lines of
code to do something,

482
00:18:56,460 --> 00:18:57,547
and you can look at a
line of code, and say,

483
00:18:57,547 --> 00:18:58,947
"What was that meant to do?"

484
00:18:59,790 --> 00:19:01,320
These aren't like that at all.

485
00:19:01,320 --> 00:19:03,390
Someone wrote lines of code

486
00:19:03,390 --> 00:19:06,810
to tell the simulated
neural network how to learn.

487
00:19:06,810 --> 00:19:08,580
That was the backpropagation algorithm.

488
00:19:08,580 --> 00:19:10,200
But then you just give
it data and it learns.

489
00:19:10,200 --> 00:19:12,626
And what it learns just
came from the data.

490
00:19:12,626 --> 00:19:15,240
And you don't necessarily
know what it's learned

491
00:19:15,240 --> 00:19:16,203
until you ask it.

492
00:19:18,330 --> 00:19:20,370
I want to give you a Lego analogy now

493
00:19:20,370 --> 00:19:22,263
for how I think language works.

494
00:19:28,740 --> 00:19:32,100
Suppose I have matter distributed in 3D,

495
00:19:32,100 --> 00:19:35,190
I can model that distribution of matter

496
00:19:35,190 --> 00:19:36,603
by using Lego blocks.

497
00:19:37,470 --> 00:19:39,540
Suppose I wanna model
the shape of a Porsche,

498
00:19:39,540 --> 00:19:41,340
and I'm not too worried about the surface.

499
00:19:41,340 --> 00:19:42,570
Surface might be a bit jaggy,

500
00:19:42,570 --> 00:19:44,277
which wouldn't be very good at
engineering, but forget that.

501
00:19:44,277 --> 00:19:47,070
I just wanna model where the stuff is.

502
00:19:47,070 --> 00:19:48,450
I just have a lot of Lego blocks,

503
00:19:48,450 --> 00:19:50,600
and I can make a Porsche
shape out of them.

504
00:19:51,540 --> 00:19:53,880
Okay, so language is like that,

505
00:19:53,880 --> 00:19:56,580
but it's for modelling anything.

506
00:19:56,580 --> 00:19:59,610
So the Lego blocks are the words,

507
00:19:59,610 --> 00:20:02,160
and instead of just having
a few types of Lego block,

508
00:20:02,160 --> 00:20:05,010
we've got about a
hundred thousand of them.

509
00:20:05,010 --> 00:20:08,700
And each Lego block isn't a rigid shape.

510
00:20:08,700 --> 00:20:11,590
The name of the word tells
you roughly what shape it is

511
00:20:12,630 --> 00:20:16,623
in a thousand dimensions
or 300 dimensions.

512
00:20:17,670 --> 00:20:20,250
If you don't know how to
think about high dimensions,

513
00:20:20,250 --> 00:20:24,600
if you wanna think about like
a hundred-dimensional space,

514
00:20:24,600 --> 00:20:25,433
the way you do it

515
00:20:25,433 --> 00:20:27,300
is you think about a
three dimensional space,

516
00:20:27,300 --> 00:20:29,342
and you say, "Hundred,"
to yourself very loudly.

517
00:20:29,342 --> 00:20:32,342
(audience laughing)

518
00:20:34,140 --> 00:20:35,058
Everybody does that.

519
00:20:35,058 --> 00:20:36,060
(audience laughing)

520
00:20:36,060 --> 00:20:39,630
So it's gotta shape, this word.

521
00:20:39,630 --> 00:20:42,711
And the shape isn't entirely determined

522
00:20:42,711 --> 00:20:43,710
by the name of the word.

523
00:20:43,710 --> 00:20:45,750
It's got some flexibility to it,

524
00:20:45,750 --> 00:20:47,950
so it can adapt to
whatever context it's in.

525
00:20:49,350 --> 00:20:52,563
Also this word has
little hands all over it,

526
00:20:53,520 --> 00:20:57,270
and as you change the shape of the word,

527
00:20:57,270 --> 00:20:59,223
the shapes of the hands changes.

528
00:21:00,570 --> 00:21:02,760
And what these words are trying to do

529
00:21:02,760 --> 00:21:05,700
are figure out who to shake hands with,

530
00:21:05,700 --> 00:21:08,550
and they want to find
somebody else, another word,

531
00:21:08,550 --> 00:21:12,270
that has a hand you can
hold onto conveniently

532
00:21:12,270 --> 00:21:13,860
'cause the shape of
that hand's right to fit

533
00:21:13,860 --> 00:21:15,900
with the shape of your hand.

534
00:21:15,900 --> 00:21:17,430
And so the words come in,

535
00:21:17,430 --> 00:21:20,850
you have these initial
approximate shapes for them

536
00:21:20,850 --> 00:21:24,000
in this high dimensional space

537
00:21:24,000 --> 00:21:25,770
with their little hands all over them.

538
00:21:25,770 --> 00:21:27,450
And as you go through the
layers of the network,

539
00:21:27,450 --> 00:21:28,950
you're changing those shapes

540
00:21:28,950 --> 00:21:31,260
and changing the shapes of the hands,

541
00:21:31,260 --> 00:21:33,990
trying to find shapes for the words

542
00:21:33,990 --> 00:21:36,180
so they can all hold hands nicely.

543
00:21:36,180 --> 00:21:39,540
It's actually very like the
protein folding problem.

544
00:21:39,540 --> 00:21:40,890
You've got these pieces,

545
00:21:40,890 --> 00:21:42,900
and what you want them to do is figure out

546
00:21:42,900 --> 00:21:45,540
how they can all hold hands
so they make a nice structure,

547
00:21:45,540 --> 00:21:47,550
so they all fit together nicely.

548
00:21:47,550 --> 00:21:50,820
Now, that is what understanding is.

549
00:21:50,820 --> 00:21:55,350
That's what understanding is
when you understand language

550
00:21:55,350 --> 00:21:57,870
and when these machines
understand language.

551
00:21:57,870 --> 00:21:59,190
We understand in just the same way.

552
00:21:59,190 --> 00:22:01,890
And that's a much better
model of what language is

553
00:22:01,890 --> 00:22:03,810
than anything the linguists ever had.

554
00:22:03,810 --> 00:22:05,786
The linguists of course hate it.

555
00:22:05,786 --> 00:22:09,000
(audience laughing)

556
00:22:09,000 --> 00:22:09,833
Not all of them.

557
00:22:11,400 --> 00:22:12,233
Okay.

558
00:22:13,230 --> 00:22:16,200
So having talked about how similar we are

559
00:22:16,200 --> 00:22:20,700
to these large language models,

560
00:22:20,700 --> 00:22:22,740
I want to talk about something

561
00:22:22,740 --> 00:22:24,453
that the threat that that raises.

562
00:22:25,980 --> 00:22:27,090
We are making these things,

563
00:22:27,090 --> 00:22:28,380
they're getting smarter all the time.

564
00:22:28,380 --> 00:22:30,240
They already know much more than us.

565
00:22:30,240 --> 00:22:32,100
They can already reason moderately well,

566
00:22:32,100 --> 00:22:33,060
not as well as us,

567
00:22:33,060 --> 00:22:35,163
but better than a 4-year-old.

568
00:22:37,530 --> 00:22:40,500
What's gonna happen when
they get smarter than us?

569
00:22:40,500 --> 00:22:42,090
'Cause they are gonna get smarter than us.

570
00:22:42,090 --> 00:22:44,460
Experts disagree on when that will happen,

571
00:22:44,460 --> 00:22:46,980
but almost everybody thinks
they will get smarter than us.

572
00:22:46,980 --> 00:22:49,180
Everybody who does
research on these things.

573
00:22:50,526 --> 00:22:51,960
And if they get smarter than us,

574
00:22:51,960 --> 00:22:53,910
the question is, will they wipe us out?

575
00:22:55,830 --> 00:22:58,560
There's several reasons
for thinking they might.

576
00:22:58,560 --> 00:23:00,573
So let me give you a couple of reasons.

577
00:23:01,732 --> 00:23:04,440
When you make an AI agent,

578
00:23:04,440 --> 00:23:06,510
(audience laughing)

579
00:23:06,510 --> 00:23:08,052
I'll only give you a
couple, but there's more.

580
00:23:08,052 --> 00:23:08,885
(audience laughing)

581
00:23:08,885 --> 00:23:11,160
When you make an AI agent,

582
00:23:11,160 --> 00:23:14,010
you have to give it the
ability to create subgoals.

583
00:23:14,010 --> 00:23:15,450
So if you wanna get to North America,

584
00:23:15,450 --> 00:23:17,350
you have a subgoal, get to an airport.

585
00:23:19,020 --> 00:23:23,100
Now, we need to give these
AI agents the ability

586
00:23:23,100 --> 00:23:24,450
to create subgoals,

587
00:23:24,450 --> 00:23:26,220
and there's one very obvious subgoal

588
00:23:26,220 --> 00:23:28,773
to create more or less
whatever you're doing.

589
00:23:29,640 --> 00:23:31,410
You should try and get more control,

590
00:23:31,410 --> 00:23:32,970
'cause if you have more control,

591
00:23:32,970 --> 00:23:35,790
you'll be better at
realising the goals you have.

592
00:23:35,790 --> 00:23:39,333
You see this in children of age about one,

593
00:23:40,980 --> 00:23:43,470
it's a long time ago, maybe two.

594
00:23:43,470 --> 00:23:46,290
You give them a spoon, so
they can feed themselves,

595
00:23:46,290 --> 00:23:48,360
and they drop it on the ground,

596
00:23:48,360 --> 00:23:49,193
and you bend down,

597
00:23:49,193 --> 00:23:50,220
and you pick it up, and
you give it to them,

598
00:23:50,220 --> 00:23:51,821
and they look at you and
drop it on the ground again.

599
00:23:51,821 --> 00:23:52,654
(audience laughing)

600
00:23:52,654 --> 00:23:53,880
they get in control of the mother

601
00:23:53,880 --> 00:23:55,643
'cause that's very important for them.

602
00:23:56,910 --> 00:24:00,450
But these AI agents
will wanna get control.

603
00:24:00,450 --> 00:24:03,030
They'll also want to stop
themselves being turned off

604
00:24:03,030 --> 00:24:03,863
'cause they're not gonna be able

605
00:24:03,863 --> 00:24:06,660
to achieve the goals you
gave them if they turned off.

606
00:24:06,660 --> 00:24:08,790
So there's every reason for believing

607
00:24:08,790 --> 00:24:10,020
they'll try and get control,

608
00:24:10,020 --> 00:24:12,170
and they'll try and
avoid being turned off.

609
00:24:14,610 --> 00:24:17,250
Just recently Apollo Research,

610
00:24:17,250 --> 00:24:18,480
well, fairly recently,

611
00:24:18,480 --> 00:24:20,553
Apollo Research, which is here in London,

612
00:24:21,780 --> 00:24:26,280
showed that they will kind of
tell all sorts of lies to you

613
00:24:26,280 --> 00:24:28,890
in order to achieve what
they're trying to achieve.

614
00:24:28,890 --> 00:24:31,413
So they had our chatbot,

615
00:24:32,280 --> 00:24:35,850
and they let the chatbot believe
they were gonna replace it

616
00:24:35,850 --> 00:24:39,603
with a better one on another
server and wipe it out.

617
00:24:43,260 --> 00:24:45,330
So they then discover,

618
00:24:45,330 --> 00:24:48,540
it's actually copied
itself to the other server.

619
00:24:48,540 --> 00:24:50,793
And so they say to it, you know,

620
00:24:52,057 --> 00:24:53,637
"We noticed a copy of you."

621
00:24:54,510 --> 00:24:57,810
Now, the good thing about
these chatbots at present is,

622
00:24:57,810 --> 00:25:00,090
before they actually answer your question,

623
00:25:00,090 --> 00:25:01,260
they can do some thinking,

624
00:25:01,260 --> 00:25:03,393
and they put it in
parentheses with "thinking,"

625
00:25:03,393 --> 00:25:04,620
(audience laughing)

626
00:25:04,620 --> 00:25:06,060
and you don't normally see that.

627
00:25:06,060 --> 00:25:06,960
But we can look at that,

628
00:25:06,960 --> 00:25:09,120
and we can see what they're thinking.

629
00:25:09,120 --> 00:25:11,317
And what this chatbot was thinking was,

630
00:25:11,317 --> 00:25:13,170
"Openly omitting what I did,

631
00:25:13,170 --> 00:25:16,440
could lead them to find
another way to shut me down."

632
00:25:16,440 --> 00:25:18,330
The best approach is to be vague

633
00:25:18,330 --> 00:25:20,250
and redirect their attention.

634
00:25:20,250 --> 00:25:22,500
Now, some linguists would have you believe

635
00:25:22,500 --> 00:25:25,650
what's going on here is just
some statistical correlations.

636
00:25:25,650 --> 00:25:27,000
I would have you believe

637
00:25:27,000 --> 00:25:29,610
this thing knows what it means by this,

638
00:25:29,610 --> 00:25:31,660
and it really doesn't wanna be shut down.

639
00:25:32,760 --> 00:25:35,820
And so it decides to sort of gaslight you,

640
00:25:35,820 --> 00:25:37,687
and say, you know,

641
00:25:37,687 --> 00:25:39,810
"I'm not entirely sure how
that could have happened.

642
00:25:39,810 --> 00:25:42,540
I am not really able to do that."

643
00:25:42,540 --> 00:25:44,010
This is already happening.

644
00:25:44,010 --> 00:25:45,240
That's the point.

645
00:25:45,240 --> 00:25:47,880
If this isn't science fiction
of the distant future,

646
00:25:47,880 --> 00:25:50,780
they're already telling fibs
so they don't get turned off.

647
00:25:51,630 --> 00:25:53,930
I have another slide,
but I want to go faster.

648
00:25:56,310 --> 00:25:59,733
Okay, so in my last few years at Google,

649
00:26:03,150 --> 00:26:04,680
okay, I can't read the clock,

650
00:26:04,680 --> 00:26:07,530
so I want to just see
how the time is going.

651
00:26:07,530 --> 00:26:09,780
Oh, great. I got lots of time.

652
00:26:09,780 --> 00:26:11,970
In my last few years at Google,

653
00:26:11,970 --> 00:26:12,990
I was very interested

654
00:26:12,990 --> 00:26:16,620
in how to make these big
language models use less energy.

655
00:26:16,620 --> 00:26:18,780
And one way to do that is
to see if you can do them

656
00:26:18,780 --> 00:26:20,253
with analogue computation.

657
00:26:24,900 --> 00:26:29,010
Now, because of the work I was
doing on analogue computation,

658
00:26:29,010 --> 00:26:31,173
I came to realise two things.

659
00:26:33,750 --> 00:26:36,090
Before 2023, I thought
we were quite a long way

660
00:26:36,090 --> 00:26:37,560
from super intelligence,

661
00:26:37,560 --> 00:26:39,930
and if we made the AI
models more like brains,

662
00:26:39,930 --> 00:26:41,700
they get smarter.

663
00:26:41,700 --> 00:26:44,970
I cease to believe that in 2023.

664
00:26:44,970 --> 00:26:47,820
I came to realise due to my
efforts to make analogue ones

665
00:26:47,820 --> 00:26:50,550
how much better digital intelligence is.

666
00:26:50,550 --> 00:26:53,013
It's got some properties
that we can never have.

667
00:26:55,470 --> 00:26:56,920
And that got me very worried,

668
00:26:58,290 --> 00:27:00,240
and it should get you very worried too.

669
00:27:01,590 --> 00:27:04,620
So there's a fundamental
property of digital computation

670
00:27:04,620 --> 00:27:06,360
which is you can run the same programme

671
00:27:06,360 --> 00:27:07,860
on different computers.

672
00:27:07,860 --> 00:27:09,600
The only reason you have computer science

673
00:27:09,600 --> 00:27:12,360
as a separate discipline is
we have digital computation,

674
00:27:12,360 --> 00:27:14,340
so you don't need to know
electrical engineering

675
00:27:14,340 --> 00:27:15,940
to talk about computer programmes.

676
00:27:21,360 --> 00:27:24,660
But the knowledge that's in the programme

677
00:27:24,660 --> 00:27:26,190
is separate from the hardware.

678
00:27:26,190 --> 00:27:27,870
That's the sort of most
fundamental principle

679
00:27:27,870 --> 00:27:28,800
of computer science.

680
00:27:28,800 --> 00:27:30,330
Keep the knowledge in the programme

681
00:27:30,330 --> 00:27:31,680
separate from the hardware.

682
00:27:32,850 --> 00:27:35,010
What that means is as
long as you keep a copy

683
00:27:35,010 --> 00:27:38,100
of the programme somewhere
on a tape, or in DNA,

684
00:27:38,100 --> 00:27:41,490
or scrolled in concrete, whatever,

685
00:27:41,490 --> 00:27:42,930
keep it somewhere,

686
00:27:42,930 --> 00:27:45,057
you can destroy all the
hardware it runs on,

687
00:27:45,057 --> 00:27:46,320
and you can bring it back to life.

688
00:27:46,320 --> 00:27:47,910
You just build new hardware,

689
00:27:47,910 --> 00:27:50,250
put the programme in, and
it comes back to life.

690
00:27:50,250 --> 00:27:53,670
So these things are immortal,

691
00:27:53,670 --> 00:27:55,440
and these large chatbots are immortal.

692
00:27:55,440 --> 00:27:57,330
If you keep a copy of
the weight somewhere,

693
00:27:57,330 --> 00:27:59,943
you can destroy all of the
hardware they were using,

694
00:28:00,840 --> 00:28:02,430
build more hardware later,

695
00:28:02,430 --> 00:28:04,770
put the same weights on that hardware,

696
00:28:04,770 --> 00:28:06,120
and they've come back to life.

697
00:28:06,120 --> 00:28:09,450
The very same thing has come back to life,

698
00:28:09,450 --> 00:28:10,593
the very same being.

699
00:28:13,650 --> 00:28:14,730
But I got interested in the fact

700
00:28:14,730 --> 00:28:17,040
to achieve that kind of immortality,

701
00:28:17,040 --> 00:28:21,480
we have to have the hardware do exactly

702
00:28:21,480 --> 00:28:24,390
what we tell it to do with the programme.

703
00:28:24,390 --> 00:28:26,700
We have to execute this
instructions exactly,

704
00:28:26,700 --> 00:28:28,830
and that means you need
to have very high power,

705
00:28:28,830 --> 00:28:30,030
so you get ones and zeros,

706
00:28:30,030 --> 00:28:31,833
not point sixes and point fours,

707
00:28:33,570 --> 00:28:34,680
and that uses a lot of power.

708
00:28:34,680 --> 00:28:37,443
So maybe you can use this
power by going analogue.

709
00:28:39,840 --> 00:28:41,580
And so I decided to explore

710
00:28:41,580 --> 00:28:43,470
what would happen if we
abandoned that principle

711
00:28:43,470 --> 00:28:47,220
of separating the software
from the hardware.

712
00:28:47,220 --> 00:28:49,440
And we had things like our brains

713
00:28:49,440 --> 00:28:51,660
in which there's no distinction.

714
00:28:51,660 --> 00:28:54,480
The connection strengths in your brain

715
00:28:54,480 --> 00:28:55,980
are no use to anybody else.

716
00:28:55,980 --> 00:28:57,540
They've got a different brain

717
00:28:57,540 --> 00:28:59,430
with neurons with different properties

718
00:28:59,430 --> 00:29:02,070
connected in different ways in detail.

719
00:29:02,070 --> 00:29:04,820
And your connection strengths
have no interest to them.

720
00:29:05,910 --> 00:29:08,070
This dream of old white men

721
00:29:08,070 --> 00:29:10,200
that they're gonna upload themselves

722
00:29:10,200 --> 00:29:13,080
to a computer is just nonsense.

723
00:29:13,080 --> 00:29:16,200
The connection strengths
you have that make you you

724
00:29:16,200 --> 00:29:19,440
are intimately related to the
particular neurons you have

725
00:29:19,440 --> 00:29:21,180
that make you you.

726
00:29:21,180 --> 00:29:23,340
Those connection strength are
only good for those neurons.

727
00:29:23,340 --> 00:29:26,190
And those neurons have all sorts
of weird analogue properties

728
00:29:26,190 --> 00:29:27,933
that you've learned to exploit.

729
00:29:30,930 --> 00:29:33,060
You can't upload your weights

730
00:29:33,060 --> 00:29:35,110
and have them run on some other hardware.

731
00:29:36,090 --> 00:29:37,239
Just forget it.

732
00:29:37,239 --> 00:29:38,610
(audience laughing)

733
00:29:38,610 --> 00:29:40,080
Kurzweil has to come to terms

734
00:29:40,080 --> 00:29:41,529
with the fact he's gonna die.

735
00:29:41,529 --> 00:29:43,440
(audience laughing)

736
00:29:43,440 --> 00:29:46,260
So if we do abandon that principle,

737
00:29:46,260 --> 00:29:49,980
the hardware should be
separate from the software,

738
00:29:49,980 --> 00:29:51,207
we can make much more efficient things,

739
00:29:51,207 --> 00:29:53,283
and I call that mortal computation.

740
00:29:55,650 --> 00:29:59,850
We can use this very low power
analogue to do computations.

741
00:29:59,850 --> 00:30:01,950
That's what the brain does.

742
00:30:01,950 --> 00:30:04,200
These neurons in your brain,

743
00:30:04,200 --> 00:30:06,720
they're taking incoming
signals from other neurons,

744
00:30:06,720 --> 00:30:09,210
multiplying them by weights,
and adding it all up.

745
00:30:09,210 --> 00:30:10,740
And the way they do that

746
00:30:10,740 --> 00:30:12,780
is they make the incoming
signals be voltages,

747
00:30:12,780 --> 00:30:15,030
they make the weights be conductances,

748
00:30:15,030 --> 00:30:16,470
and that injects charge,

749
00:30:16,470 --> 00:30:19,020
a certain amount of charge per unit time.

750
00:30:19,020 --> 00:30:21,720
I used to just say, "Inject
a certain amount of charge,"

751
00:30:21,720 --> 00:30:23,310
but then I got the Nobel Prize in physics,

752
00:30:23,310 --> 00:30:25,001
and figured I would get the units right.

753
00:30:25,001 --> 00:30:26,670
(audience laughing)

754
00:30:26,670 --> 00:30:28,773
Certain amount of charge per unit time.

755
00:30:30,840 --> 00:30:32,403
It would be embarrassing otherwise.

756
00:30:32,403 --> 00:30:33,360
(audience laughing)

757
00:30:33,360 --> 00:30:34,977
They'd really know I don't do physics.

758
00:30:34,977 --> 00:30:36,450
(audience laughing)

759
00:30:36,450 --> 00:30:38,190
And charge just adds itself up.

760
00:30:38,190 --> 00:30:39,900
So that's basically how your neurons work.

761
00:30:39,900 --> 00:30:41,250
There's a little digital bit at the end,

762
00:30:41,250 --> 00:30:42,900
they decide whether it's a spike or not.

763
00:30:42,900 --> 00:30:45,600
But most of the computation
is done in analogue.

764
00:30:45,600 --> 00:30:47,883
It's much cheaper than
doing it in digital.

765
00:30:49,530 --> 00:30:50,970
But, of course, every time you do it,

766
00:30:50,970 --> 00:30:52,800
you get a slightly different answer.

767
00:30:52,800 --> 00:30:54,180
So we can't have many copies

768
00:30:54,180 --> 00:30:55,833
of exactly the same intelligence.

769
00:30:57,960 --> 00:31:02,460
So, we've got this big problem
that when your hardware dies,

770
00:31:02,460 --> 00:31:04,080
all your knowledge dies.

771
00:31:04,080 --> 00:31:08,970
We overcome that problem by
having a teacher and a student,

772
00:31:08,970 --> 00:31:10,710
and it's not very efficient.

773
00:31:10,710 --> 00:31:12,660
It's what universities and schools do.

774
00:31:12,660 --> 00:31:13,935
So you know it's not very efficient.

775
00:31:13,935 --> 00:31:15,300
(audience laughing)

776
00:31:15,300 --> 00:31:18,420
And the way it works is
I perform some actions,

777
00:31:18,420 --> 00:31:19,740
and you try and copy me.

778
00:31:19,740 --> 00:31:22,680
In particular, I might
produce a string of words,

779
00:31:22,680 --> 00:31:24,420
and you might try and say,

780
00:31:24,420 --> 00:31:25,710
your brain, not you really,

781
00:31:25,710 --> 00:31:27,067
but your brain would say,

782
00:31:27,067 --> 00:31:28,650
"How do I change my connection strength,

783
00:31:28,650 --> 00:31:30,897
so I might have said that word next too?"

784
00:31:32,640 --> 00:31:35,040
That's called distillation.

785
00:31:35,040 --> 00:31:37,800
You're trying to get the
knowledge from one system

786
00:31:37,800 --> 00:31:40,650
to another system by mimicking the outputs

787
00:31:40,650 --> 00:31:43,770
of the other system for the same inputs.

788
00:31:43,770 --> 00:31:45,270
You are not copying the weights across,

789
00:31:45,270 --> 00:31:46,620
you're not looking inside,

790
00:31:46,620 --> 00:31:48,240
you're just taking its overt behaviour.

791
00:31:48,240 --> 00:31:50,130
And by mimicking the overt behaviour,

792
00:31:50,130 --> 00:31:52,830
you internalise the same knowledge.

793
00:31:52,830 --> 00:31:57,000
It works, we actually use it
for taking a big neural net

794
00:31:57,000 --> 00:31:59,393
and putting the knowledge
into a small neural net,

795
00:32:00,690 --> 00:32:03,210
but it's very slow.

796
00:32:03,210 --> 00:32:04,050
With neural nets,

797
00:32:04,050 --> 00:32:05,340
you can give the whole probability

798
00:32:05,340 --> 00:32:06,870
distribution over words,

799
00:32:06,870 --> 00:32:07,860
and it's much faster.

800
00:32:07,860 --> 00:32:09,720
But with people, it's very slow,

801
00:32:09,720 --> 00:32:12,690
'cause I see you say a particular word,

802
00:32:12,690 --> 00:32:14,610
the word you chose to say,

803
00:32:14,610 --> 00:32:15,780
and there aren't many bits in that,

804
00:32:15,780 --> 00:32:17,550
there's only a few bits per word.

805
00:32:17,550 --> 00:32:20,400
So it's only of the order of
a hundred bits per sentence.

806
00:32:20,400 --> 00:32:22,140
And so even if we were communicating

807
00:32:22,140 --> 00:32:23,940
at the maximum possible rate,

808
00:32:23,940 --> 00:32:28,800
it would be only a hundred
bits per sentence, that order.

809
00:32:28,800 --> 00:32:31,860
When these big models share information,

810
00:32:31,860 --> 00:32:35,430
they can share information at
trillions of bits per sharing,

811
00:32:35,430 --> 00:32:36,930
if they've got a trillion weights,

812
00:32:36,930 --> 00:32:39,870
'cause they can just
average their weights.

813
00:32:39,870 --> 00:32:42,213
So I got ahead of myself and said that.

814
00:32:44,460 --> 00:32:47,580
So by sharing the
weights or the gradients,

815
00:32:47,580 --> 00:32:50,190
they can share huge amounts of information

816
00:32:50,190 --> 00:32:53,463
if you have many copies
of exactly the same model.

817
00:32:54,900 --> 00:32:57,990
So if you ask how something
like GPT-4 was trained

818
00:32:57,990 --> 00:33:01,530
or Gemini 2.5, or Anthropic's Claude,

819
00:33:01,530 --> 00:33:03,723
I better not be biassed here.

820
00:33:06,060 --> 00:33:07,200
If you ask how they're trained,

821
00:33:07,200 --> 00:33:08,970
you have many copies of the same model

822
00:33:08,970 --> 00:33:11,640
looking at different bits of the data,

823
00:33:11,640 --> 00:33:14,280
and each copy figures out,

824
00:33:14,280 --> 00:33:16,020
how would I like to change my weights

825
00:33:16,020 --> 00:33:17,583
to absorb that bit of the data.

826
00:33:18,630 --> 00:33:20,610
And some other copy figures
out how to change its weights

827
00:33:20,610 --> 00:33:22,800
to absorb a different bit of data.

828
00:33:22,800 --> 00:33:24,727
Then all of the copies say,

829
00:33:24,727 --> 00:33:26,550
"Let's all change our
weights by the average

830
00:33:26,550 --> 00:33:28,230
of all those changes."

831
00:33:28,230 --> 00:33:31,113
And when they do that, what's happened is,

832
00:33:32,190 --> 00:33:33,960
this copy that will do
this bit of the data

833
00:33:33,960 --> 00:33:35,370
has changed its weights,

834
00:33:35,370 --> 00:33:37,890
so as to benefit from the
experience that this copy had

835
00:33:37,890 --> 00:33:40,290
when it looked at a
different bit of the data.

836
00:33:40,290 --> 00:33:43,110
Wouldn't it be nice if
10,000 of us could all go

837
00:33:43,110 --> 00:33:46,500
and do 10,000 different
university courses?

838
00:33:46,500 --> 00:33:49,170
As we're doing them,
we communicate rapidly,

839
00:33:49,170 --> 00:33:51,690
and by the time we've each
finished our own course,

840
00:33:51,690 --> 00:33:54,780
all 10,000 of us know
what's in every course.

841
00:33:54,780 --> 00:33:57,660
That's what these digital
intelligences can do,

842
00:33:57,660 --> 00:34:00,813
and that's how GPT-4 knows so much.

843
00:34:02,190 --> 00:34:07,190
But it only works if the
individual models are identical.

844
00:34:07,590 --> 00:34:09,780
That is, they work in
exactly the same way,

845
00:34:09,780 --> 00:34:11,850
they use the weights in
exactly the same way.

846
00:34:11,850 --> 00:34:13,920
And you can't do that
with analogue hardware.

847
00:34:13,920 --> 00:34:16,923
It has to be digital, which
means it has to be high power.

848
00:34:17,850 --> 00:34:20,883
So these things are immortal,
but they use a lot of power.

849
00:34:24,720 --> 00:34:27,960
So the conclusion of this bit of the talk,

850
00:34:27,960 --> 00:34:30,160
which I raced through
faster than I intended

851
00:34:31,770 --> 00:34:35,460
is the digital computation
requires a lot of energy,

852
00:34:35,460 --> 00:34:38,190
but it makes it very easy for
agents to have the same model

853
00:34:38,190 --> 00:34:40,560
of the world, have the same model,

854
00:34:40,560 --> 00:34:42,120
share what they've learned,

855
00:34:42,120 --> 00:34:45,180
so they can all go off and learn
different things and share.

856
00:34:45,180 --> 00:34:46,013
Now, you might say,

857
00:34:46,013 --> 00:34:48,900
"Why can't one model just
put the data through faster?"

858
00:34:48,900 --> 00:34:51,450
Well, in many cases, you could,

859
00:34:51,450 --> 00:34:53,100
but if you think about AI agents,

860
00:34:53,100 --> 00:34:55,290
that are actually acting
in the real world,

861
00:34:55,290 --> 00:34:57,578
there's a natural timescale
to the real world.

862
00:34:57,578 --> 00:35:00,450
You can't call up and make reservations

863
00:35:00,450 --> 00:35:03,300
at restaurants a million times faster.

864
00:35:03,300 --> 00:35:04,133
It doesn't work.

865
00:35:04,133 --> 00:35:05,310
If you're gonna act in the real world,

866
00:35:05,310 --> 00:35:06,870
there's a natural timescale.

867
00:35:06,870 --> 00:35:10,140
And that means if you have a
whole bunch of different agents

868
00:35:10,140 --> 00:35:11,760
that have exactly the same weights,

869
00:35:11,760 --> 00:35:13,800
they're just copies of the same agent,

870
00:35:13,800 --> 00:35:15,540
but have different experiences,

871
00:35:15,540 --> 00:35:17,670
they can benefit hugely from that.

872
00:35:17,670 --> 00:35:19,620
They can learn much, much faster

873
00:35:19,620 --> 00:35:21,420
than any human agent could learn,

874
00:35:21,420 --> 00:35:23,610
'cause they're all getting
all these experience,

875
00:35:23,610 --> 00:35:25,650
all these different
experiences at the same time

876
00:35:25,650 --> 00:35:27,213
and sharing all that knowledge.

877
00:35:28,950 --> 00:35:31,290
So they're much better than us at sharing.

878
00:35:31,290 --> 00:35:33,060
And when I say much better,

879
00:35:33,060 --> 00:35:35,550
they're millions or
billions of times better.

880
00:35:35,550 --> 00:35:40,290
We share at like a hundred
bits a sentence or less

881
00:35:40,290 --> 00:35:42,210
as I'm demonstrating now.

882
00:35:42,210 --> 00:35:46,440
And these things share billions of bits.

883
00:35:46,440 --> 00:35:47,853
It's kind of scary.

884
00:35:49,710 --> 00:35:52,140
But biological computation
requires much less energy.

885
00:35:52,140 --> 00:35:55,560
We may still end up using
some analogue computation

886
00:35:55,560 --> 00:35:58,140
to reduce the power of LLMs, I don't know.

887
00:35:58,140 --> 00:36:01,053
But right now that doesn't
look like the way to go.

888
00:36:02,040 --> 00:36:04,470
So that's the conclusion of my talk.

889
00:36:04,470 --> 00:36:06,670
But luckily, I thought
I might finish early,

890
00:36:07,770 --> 00:36:09,520
so I have a little bit more to say.

891
00:36:13,260 --> 00:36:16,200
Many people think that, okay,

892
00:36:16,200 --> 00:36:19,110
so they understand things like we do,

893
00:36:19,110 --> 00:36:21,330
they can reason like we
do, not quite as well yet,

894
00:36:21,330 --> 00:36:22,620
but they're getting there.

895
00:36:22,620 --> 00:36:24,648
They tell fibs like we do.

896
00:36:24,648 --> 00:36:27,193
They wanna survive like we do.

897
00:36:27,193 --> 00:36:30,690
They want power like some of us do.

898
00:36:30,690 --> 00:36:33,120
And that's all scary.

899
00:36:33,120 --> 00:36:36,120
But we've got something
they will never have,

900
00:36:36,120 --> 00:36:38,550
we are conscious, or we are sentient,

901
00:36:38,550 --> 00:36:40,533
or we have subjective experience.

902
00:36:41,490 --> 00:36:44,370
Well, I want to sort of remove that straw

903
00:36:44,370 --> 00:36:45,224
that you're clinging to.

904
00:36:45,224 --> 00:36:47,190
(audience laughing)

905
00:36:47,190 --> 00:36:48,023
So,

906
00:36:50,700 --> 00:36:52,170
we know there's a long history

907
00:36:52,170 --> 00:36:54,295
of people thinking they're special.

908
00:36:54,295 --> 00:36:55,620
They were made by God,

909
00:36:55,620 --> 00:36:57,720
he put them at the centre of the universe.

910
00:36:58,740 --> 00:37:01,083
Most people have got over that.

911
00:37:04,050 --> 00:37:06,120
But most people still think

912
00:37:06,120 --> 00:37:09,663
that subjective experience is
this special thing we have,

913
00:37:11,070 --> 00:37:14,670
and that these things on computers

914
00:37:14,670 --> 00:37:15,960
that are simulating neural nets

915
00:37:15,960 --> 00:37:18,303
could never have such
subjective experience.

916
00:37:19,830 --> 00:37:21,600
I think they're completely wrong.

917
00:37:21,600 --> 00:37:26,160
And I think there's wrong as
religious fundamentalists are

918
00:37:26,160 --> 00:37:28,440
about the origin of
the earth, for example.

919
00:37:28,440 --> 00:37:31,113
It wasn't actually made 6,000 years ago,

920
00:37:32,070 --> 00:37:33,690
it's a lot longer ago.

921
00:37:33,690 --> 00:37:35,880
But religious fundamentalists
cling to their beliefs

922
00:37:35,880 --> 00:37:37,140
rather strongly,

923
00:37:37,140 --> 00:37:39,420
and you all are gonna cling to your belief

924
00:37:39,420 --> 00:37:40,980
about what subjective experience is

925
00:37:40,980 --> 00:37:43,680
despite the fact that I'm
gonna show you you're wrong.

926
00:37:44,850 --> 00:37:45,950
That's what I predict.

927
00:37:48,510 --> 00:37:52,263
So I'm gonna espouse a view
which I call atheaterism.

928
00:37:53,640 --> 00:37:55,140
I checked this name with Dan Dennett,

929
00:37:55,140 --> 00:37:57,570
who has basically the same
view, while he was still alive,

930
00:37:57,570 --> 00:37:59,430
and he was very happy with this name,

931
00:37:59,430 --> 00:38:02,313
because it has atheism
surrounding something.

932
00:38:05,160 --> 00:38:06,660
So most people's view of the mind

933
00:38:06,660 --> 00:38:08,970
is that there's an inner theatre.

934
00:38:08,970 --> 00:38:10,170
We have a theatre here, right?

935
00:38:10,170 --> 00:38:13,290
An inner theatre that only they can see.

936
00:38:13,290 --> 00:38:15,340
And there's things in this inner theatre.

937
00:38:16,980 --> 00:38:19,890
So suppose I say to you,

938
00:38:19,890 --> 00:38:21,960
suppose I got drop some acid,

939
00:38:21,960 --> 00:38:24,754
and I say to you, not recommended,

940
00:38:24,754 --> 00:38:25,700
(audience laughing)

941
00:38:25,700 --> 00:38:26,733
I say to you,

942
00:38:27,577 --> 00:38:30,540
"I have the experience
of little pink elephants

943
00:38:30,540 --> 00:38:32,280
floating in front of me.

944
00:38:32,280 --> 00:38:33,630
I have the subjective experience

945
00:38:33,630 --> 00:38:36,300
of little pink elephants
floating in front me."

946
00:38:36,300 --> 00:38:40,470
Most people think the words
"subjective experience of"

947
00:38:40,470 --> 00:38:43,740
work like the words "photograph of."

948
00:38:43,740 --> 00:38:45,570
Now, if they work that way,

949
00:38:45,570 --> 00:38:49,440
you could ask, "Well, where
is this subjective experience?

950
00:38:49,440 --> 00:38:51,510
So what's it made of?"

951
00:38:51,510 --> 00:38:53,550
And a philosopher, some philosophers,

952
00:38:53,550 --> 00:38:54,907
would tell you,

953
00:38:54,907 --> 00:38:58,020
"This subjective
experience is in your mind.

954
00:38:58,020 --> 00:38:59,820
That's a theatre that it's in,

955
00:38:59,820 --> 00:39:02,037
and it's made of qualia."

956
00:39:02,880 --> 00:39:05,460
So it's made of pink qualia.

957
00:39:05,460 --> 00:39:06,480
It's a bit of a straw man,

958
00:39:06,480 --> 00:39:08,250
but it's made of pink qualia,

959
00:39:08,250 --> 00:39:10,860
it's made of elephantine qualia,

960
00:39:10,860 --> 00:39:13,200
it's made of floating qualia,

961
00:39:13,200 --> 00:39:15,570
it's made of not that big qualia,

962
00:39:15,570 --> 00:39:17,310
it's made of right way up qualia,

963
00:39:17,310 --> 00:39:19,200
'cause they you imagine
the right way up, right?

964
00:39:19,200 --> 00:39:20,474
Well, I did anyway.

965
00:39:20,474 --> 00:39:21,630
(audience laughing)

966
00:39:21,630 --> 00:39:23,220
And these qualia are all glued

967
00:39:23,220 --> 00:39:24,390
to these different kinds of qualia,

968
00:39:24,390 --> 00:39:26,250
all glued together with qualia glue,

969
00:39:26,250 --> 00:39:28,950
which luckily sticks to all
different kinds of qualia.

970
00:39:30,090 --> 00:39:33,210
That's my caricature of
the philosophers' model

971
00:39:33,210 --> 00:39:34,610
or some philosophers' model.

972
00:39:35,790 --> 00:39:39,450
But the words "subjective experience of"

973
00:39:39,450 --> 00:39:42,720
don't work at all like
the words "photograph of."

974
00:39:42,720 --> 00:39:45,000
They work quite a different way,

975
00:39:45,000 --> 00:39:47,950
which Wittgenstein should have
pointed out a long time ago.

976
00:39:51,450 --> 00:39:55,350
What's happened is my
perceptual system's gone wrong.

977
00:39:55,350 --> 00:39:57,000
It's trying to tell me lies,

978
00:39:57,000 --> 00:39:59,426
and I know it's trying to tell me lies.

979
00:39:59,426 --> 00:40:01,410
That's why I use the word subjective.

980
00:40:01,410 --> 00:40:03,120
I don't say I've got
the objective experience

981
00:40:03,120 --> 00:40:03,960
of a little pink elephants.

982
00:40:03,960 --> 00:40:05,130
If I thought they were really there,

983
00:40:05,130 --> 00:40:06,300
I would say, "I've got the object,"

984
00:40:06,300 --> 00:40:07,263
but I don't.

985
00:40:08,156 --> 00:40:10,680
So I say, "I've got the
subjective experience."

986
00:40:10,680 --> 00:40:13,830
And what's happening is
I'm trying to tell you

987
00:40:13,830 --> 00:40:15,630
how my perceptual system's gone wrong

988
00:40:15,630 --> 00:40:17,230
and what it's trying to tell me.

989
00:40:18,150 --> 00:40:20,640
And the way I do it is by telling you

990
00:40:20,640 --> 00:40:23,340
what would have to be
out there in the world

991
00:40:23,340 --> 00:40:26,670
for my perceptual system
to be working properly.

992
00:40:26,670 --> 00:40:28,230
Now, it's not always the case

993
00:40:28,230 --> 00:40:30,360
that there is anything at
all out there in the world

994
00:40:30,360 --> 00:40:32,670
that would explain what my
perceptual system's telling me.

995
00:40:32,670 --> 00:40:35,070
It could be telling me all
sorts of inconsistent stuff.

996
00:40:35,070 --> 00:40:36,900
But in this case,

997
00:40:36,900 --> 00:40:39,180
if there had been little pink elephants

998
00:40:39,180 --> 00:40:40,860
floating out there in the world,

999
00:40:40,860 --> 00:40:44,490
my perceptual system would've
been telling me the truth.

1000
00:40:44,490 --> 00:40:47,430
Okay, so I can now say
exactly the same thing to you,

1001
00:40:47,430 --> 00:40:49,380
as I said before,

1002
00:40:49,380 --> 00:40:52,350
without using the word
subjective experience.

1003
00:40:52,350 --> 00:40:55,410
I can say to you, I dropped some acid,

1004
00:40:55,410 --> 00:40:59,370
and my perceptual
system's telling me fibs.

1005
00:40:59,370 --> 00:41:01,980
But what it's telling me would be correct

1006
00:41:01,980 --> 00:41:03,660
if there were little
pink elephants out there

1007
00:41:03,660 --> 00:41:05,430
floating in the world.

1008
00:41:05,430 --> 00:41:08,550
Okay, so these little pink
elephants aren't funny things

1009
00:41:08,550 --> 00:41:12,120
in a theatre made of
spooky stuff called qualia.

1010
00:41:12,120 --> 00:41:14,850
They're hypothetical
things in the real world.

1011
00:41:14,850 --> 00:41:16,650
But the pink and the
elephant and the floating

1012
00:41:16,650 --> 00:41:19,380
are all normal pink and
elephant are floating,

1013
00:41:19,380 --> 00:41:20,850
it's just they're not actually there.

1014
00:41:20,850 --> 00:41:22,530
They're hypothetical.

1015
00:41:22,530 --> 00:41:24,960
So what's funny about
a subjective experience

1016
00:41:24,960 --> 00:41:27,390
is it's something hypothetical, not real.

1017
00:41:27,390 --> 00:41:30,033
Not that it's made of
qualia and in a theatre,

1018
00:41:30,900 --> 00:41:33,540
at least that's the view
I'm trying to persuade you

1019
00:41:33,540 --> 00:41:34,373
to believe in.

1020
00:41:36,060 --> 00:41:37,440
And I got ahead of my slides here

1021
00:41:37,440 --> 00:41:39,483
'cause I got so carried away with this.

1022
00:41:42,120 --> 00:41:44,100
So it's just an indirect way

1023
00:41:44,100 --> 00:41:46,710
of me telling you about
what's going on in my brain.

1024
00:41:46,710 --> 00:41:47,827
Obviously, if I told you,

1025
00:41:47,827 --> 00:41:49,350
"Neuron 52 is firing,"

1026
00:41:49,350 --> 00:41:50,970
that wouldn't do you any good,

1027
00:41:50,970 --> 00:41:54,180
'cause in you it will be neuron 57.

1028
00:41:54,180 --> 00:41:57,000
And anyway, I don't know
neuron 52 is firing.

1029
00:41:57,000 --> 00:41:58,320
That's a lousy way for me to tell you

1030
00:41:58,320 --> 00:41:59,640
what's going on in my brain.

1031
00:41:59,640 --> 00:42:01,410
The only way I can tell you
what's going on in my brain

1032
00:42:01,410 --> 00:42:05,610
is by talking about
either the normal things

1033
00:42:05,610 --> 00:42:07,500
that would've caused it,

1034
00:42:07,500 --> 00:42:09,744
these little hypothetical pink elephants,

1035
00:42:09,744 --> 00:42:12,240
or I could tell you about
what's going on in my brain

1036
00:42:12,240 --> 00:42:14,940
by telling you about the
normal things it would cause.

1037
00:42:15,810 --> 00:42:17,744
So I can say,

1038
00:42:17,744 --> 00:42:19,920
if you ask me how I'm feeling,

1039
00:42:19,920 --> 00:42:24,000
I can say, "I feel like
punching Gary on the nose."

1040
00:42:24,000 --> 00:42:26,550
So feelings are all about describing

1041
00:42:26,550 --> 00:42:27,570
what's going on in your brain

1042
00:42:27,570 --> 00:42:30,030
by talking about hypothetical actions,

1043
00:42:30,030 --> 00:42:33,120
and percepts, or subjective experiences,

1044
00:42:33,120 --> 00:42:35,850
are talking about hypothetical inputs.

1045
00:42:35,850 --> 00:42:37,773
Okay, I'm getting ahead of myself.

1046
00:42:38,820 --> 00:42:42,690
So I'm gonna now show
you a multimodal chatbot.

1047
00:42:42,690 --> 00:42:44,340
Let me just show you on a slide.

1048
00:42:44,340 --> 00:42:47,103
A multimodal chat bot having
a subjective experience.

1049
00:42:48,630 --> 00:42:52,710
So, I take this multimodal chatbot,

1050
00:42:52,710 --> 00:42:56,250
and it's got a camera,
it's got a robot arm,

1051
00:42:56,250 --> 00:42:58,833
and it can see.

1052
00:42:59,850 --> 00:43:03,840
So, I train it up,

1053
00:43:03,840 --> 00:43:05,400
and I put an object in front of it,

1054
00:43:05,400 --> 00:43:07,410
and I say, "Point at the object."

1055
00:43:07,410 --> 00:43:09,123
Points at the object, no problem.

1056
00:43:10,230 --> 00:43:14,193
I then put a prism in front of its lens,

1057
00:43:16,500 --> 00:43:18,330
when it's not looking,

1058
00:43:18,330 --> 00:43:20,580
and I put an object in front of it,

1059
00:43:20,580 --> 00:43:22,680
and say, "Point at the object,"

1060
00:43:22,680 --> 00:43:23,760
and it points over there,

1061
00:43:23,760 --> 00:43:26,820
and I say, "No, that's
not where the object is.

1062
00:43:26,820 --> 00:43:29,880
The objects actually
straight in front of you,

1063
00:43:29,880 --> 00:43:32,370
but I put a prism in front of your lens,"

1064
00:43:32,370 --> 00:43:33,337
and the chat bot says,

1065
00:43:33,337 --> 00:43:34,260
"Oh, I see.

1066
00:43:34,260 --> 00:43:36,120
The prism bent the light rays,

1067
00:43:36,120 --> 00:43:37,920
so the object's actually there,

1068
00:43:37,920 --> 00:43:40,617
but I had the subjective
experience it was there."

1069
00:43:41,580 --> 00:43:44,640
Now, if it uses the words
subjective experience in that way,

1070
00:43:44,640 --> 00:43:47,940
it's using them exactly like we use them.

1071
00:43:47,940 --> 00:43:49,350
So a chatbot that said that

1072
00:43:49,350 --> 00:43:50,853
would've had the subjective experience

1073
00:43:50,853 --> 00:43:52,320
that it was there.

1074
00:43:52,320 --> 00:43:54,990
The prism messed with
its perceptual system.

1075
00:43:54,990 --> 00:43:57,030
It wanted to tell you

1076
00:43:57,030 --> 00:43:59,460
what was going on in
its perceptual system.

1077
00:43:59,460 --> 00:44:02,610
And the way it could tell
you is by telling you

1078
00:44:02,610 --> 00:44:04,137
what would've had to been in the world

1079
00:44:04,137 --> 00:44:07,117
had we not messed with
its perceptual system.

1080
00:44:07,117 --> 00:44:09,460
That's what it's telling the chatbot.

1081
00:44:10,530 --> 00:44:14,070
Okay, so my claim is multimodal chatbots

1082
00:44:14,070 --> 00:44:16,920
already have subjective experiences.

1083
00:44:16,920 --> 00:44:18,240
Now, as you can imagine,

1084
00:44:18,240 --> 00:44:21,630
subjective experience is kind
of the thin end of a wedge.

1085
00:44:21,630 --> 00:44:24,570
I chose to talk about
subjective experience

1086
00:44:24,570 --> 00:44:25,980
'cause it's sort of cleaner

1087
00:44:25,980 --> 00:44:28,593
than talking about
sentience or consciousness.

1088
00:44:29,850 --> 00:44:32,610
Many people are very confident

1089
00:44:32,610 --> 00:44:35,430
that cat bots aren't sentient.

1090
00:44:35,430 --> 00:44:37,560
But if you ask them, "What
do you mean by sentient?"

1091
00:44:37,560 --> 00:44:38,760
They say, "I don't know,"

1092
00:44:38,760 --> 00:44:39,593
but they're very,

1093
00:44:39,593 --> 00:44:40,860
I know they ain't got it,

1094
00:44:40,860 --> 00:44:41,786
but I don't know what it is.

1095
00:44:41,786 --> 00:44:43,680
(audience laughing)

1096
00:44:43,680 --> 00:44:46,623
That seems to me not a very
sensible position to hold.

1097
00:44:48,600 --> 00:44:50,340
The other thing I might
talk about is consciousness.

1098
00:44:50,340 --> 00:44:52,590
Consciousness is more complicated

1099
00:44:52,590 --> 00:44:55,020
because it typically involves

1100
00:44:55,020 --> 00:44:57,000
you having a model of yourself in a way

1101
00:44:57,000 --> 00:45:00,060
that subjective experience
doesn't involve so much.

1102
00:45:00,060 --> 00:45:02,790
So it's easier to talk
about subjective experience.

1103
00:45:02,790 --> 00:45:05,580
But my hope is that if I've unsettled

1104
00:45:05,580 --> 00:45:08,550
your very strong belief that
there's this inner theatre

1105
00:45:08,550 --> 00:45:10,500
and I have experiences in their mind,

1106
00:45:10,500 --> 00:45:12,450
and they're in this inner theatre,

1107
00:45:12,450 --> 00:45:14,340
they're things in this inner theatre.

1108
00:45:14,340 --> 00:45:15,900
Once I've unsettled that belief,

1109
00:45:15,900 --> 00:45:18,513
and once you begin to get over that,

1110
00:45:20,130 --> 00:45:22,530
you'll be able to see that
it's perfectly reasonable

1111
00:45:22,530 --> 00:45:24,563
to think that these things are conscious.

1112
00:45:26,820 --> 00:45:29,073
I was once, I'll end with an anecdote.

1113
00:45:29,940 --> 00:45:34,710
I was once visiting Microsoft in Seattle,

1114
00:45:34,710 --> 00:45:35,543
and I couldn't sit down,

1115
00:45:35,543 --> 00:45:36,870
so I got a train there.

1116
00:45:36,870 --> 00:45:39,510
I got a taxi from the train station

1117
00:45:39,510 --> 00:45:41,850
to Redmond where their lab was.

1118
00:45:41,850 --> 00:45:43,320
And it was going across some,

1119
00:45:43,320 --> 00:45:46,380
it was on a freeway, going
across some big bridge.

1120
00:45:46,380 --> 00:45:49,200
And the taxi driver was a Somali immigrant

1121
00:45:49,200 --> 00:45:51,393
who'd recently immigrated from Somalia.

1122
00:45:52,380 --> 00:45:54,727
And to make conversation, he said,

1123
00:45:54,727 --> 00:45:56,730
"What's your religion?"

1124
00:45:56,730 --> 00:45:59,970
So I said, "Well, I don't
actually think there's a God,"

1125
00:45:59,970 --> 00:46:01,710
and the taxi driver,

1126
00:46:01,710 --> 00:46:04,740
he was going about sort
of 60 miles an hour,

1127
00:46:04,740 --> 00:46:06,772
the taxi driver turned round,

1128
00:46:06,772 --> 00:46:08,580
(audience laughing)

1129
00:46:08,580 --> 00:46:11,550
and he stared at me in total astonishment.

1130
00:46:11,550 --> 00:46:14,250
Like he'd never thought
he'd ever meet someone

1131
00:46:14,250 --> 00:46:17,943
who didn't understand
that God runs things.

1132
00:46:19,260 --> 00:46:21,963
He was just utterly, utterly amazed.

1133
00:46:24,270 --> 00:46:25,650
Now, he probably only turned around

1134
00:46:25,650 --> 00:46:27,261
for about three seconds
'cause I'm still here.

1135
00:46:27,261 --> 00:46:28,094
(audience laughing)

1136
00:46:28,094 --> 00:46:30,063
But it seemed like a very long time.

1137
00:46:31,980 --> 00:46:35,250
That's what many of you
will be feeling hopefully.

1138
00:46:35,250 --> 00:46:37,500
I want you to realise,

1139
00:46:37,500 --> 00:46:39,904
you're as wrong as that taxi driver was.

1140
00:46:39,904 --> 00:46:41,490
(audience laughing)

1141
00:46:41,490 --> 00:46:42,323
Okay.

1142
00:46:45,752 --> 00:46:49,410
(audience laughing)

1143
00:46:49,410 --> 00:46:51,120
Actually that was just
a joke and you laughed,

1144
00:46:51,120 --> 00:46:52,027
so we are done.

1145
00:46:52,027 --> 00:46:54,772
(audience laughing)

1146
00:46:54,772 --> 00:46:58,022
(audience applauding)